</md></sn><sn><md>## Humidity{.fg-red .text-center}

:::.row

::: .col-12 .col-lg-7
Humidity is a fundamental concept in meteorology, climatology, and environmental science.It refers to `the amount of water vapor present in the air`. Water vapor, though invisible, plays a crucial role in weather patterns, cloud formation, and human comfort. Understanding humidity is essential for **agriculture, health, construction, and forecasting atmospheric conditions**.
:::

::: .col-12 .col-lg-5
![image](https://scijinks.gov/what-is-humidity/rain-droplets.png)
:::

:::
 
Humidity is defined as the ==amount of water vapor in the air==. {.bar} 

Unlike other gases such as oxygen or nitrogen, water vapor is `highly variable` and depends on factors such as ==temperature, pressure, and geographical location==.

+++ In general the following several `terms` are used to quantitatively express  **humidity**
* Absolute Humidity
* Relative Humidity
* Specific Humidity
* Mixing Ratio
* Dew Point
+++</md></sn><sn><md>## Absolute Humidity{.fg-red .text-center}

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-7

Absolute humidity is the ==actual mass of water vapor present in a unit volume of air==. {.bar}

It is expressed in grams of water vapor per cubic meter of air (`g/m¬≥`).

:::

::: .col-12 .col-lg-5
![image](https://cache.careers360.mobi/media/article_images/2024/11/11/Absolute_Humidity.png)
:::

:::

* Formula:

  $$
  AH = \frac{\text{Mass of water vapor}}{\text{Volume of air}}
  $$

* Limitation: It changes with variations in air `volume` and `temperature`, making it less useful for practical meteorological purposes.
</md></sn><sn><md>## Specific Humidity{.fg-red}

Specific humidity refers to the **ratio of** the `mass of water vapor to the total mass of air` (including ==dry air and water vapor==). It is expressed in grams of water vapor per kilogram of air. Unlike relative humidity, it is *not affected by temperature changes*.

$$ \text{Specific humidity} = \frac{\text{mass of water vapor}}{\text{mass of total air}} $$

* Expressed as `g/kg`
* Very similar to absolute humidity,but ==uses the mass of total air==,*not just the volume of air*.
* It is **not affected** by the change in `pressure` or `temperature`.
* Meteorologist generally use specific humidity to express the ==water vapor content in air==.
</md></sn><sn><md>## Mixing Ratio{.fg-pink}

The *mixing ratio* is the `mass of water vapor per unit mass of dry air`, usually expressed in grams of water vapor per kilogram of dry air.

$$ \text{Mixing ratio (w)} = \frac{\text{mass of water vapor}}{\text{mass of dry air}} $$

* Expressed as `g/kg`
* Example : 10g/kg
* Range : `0 to 30`g/kg</md></sn><sn><md>## Relative Humidity{.fg-red .text-center}

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-7
Relative humidity is the **ratio of** the `actual water vapor content in the air` to the ==maximum amount the air can hold== at a given temperature . {.bar}

* Example: If the RH is `75%`, it means the **air contains `75%` of the maximum water vapor** it could hold at that temperature.
* Importance: RH is the most commonly used measure because it directly **relates to human comfort and weather conditions**.

:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-5
![image](https://scijinks.gov/what-is-humidity/relative-humidity.png)
:::

:::

### Formula{.fg-orange}

  $$
  RH = \frac{\text{Actual Vapor Pressure}}{\text{Saturation Vapor Pressure}} \times 100
  $$


#### Facts

* Expressed as a `percentage`.
* Relative humidity is a measure of `how near the air is to being saturated`.
* Relative humidity changes if  its water vapor `mixing ratio` or `temperatue` changes.</md></sn><sn><md>### Scene1{.fg-red}

